The detection system consisted of a single
detector. Detectors used in this experiment were
250-300 mm2 in area, biased to a depletion depth of
Reactions involving the emission of heavy ions
leading to low-lying states of the residual nucleus
have been studied using 42 MeV alpha-particles
incident on light target nuclei. The heavy ions
resulting from these reactions were identified by
mass number using the time-of-flight technique.
Because of the narrow temporal width of the cyclotron
beam burst (<1.5 ns FWHM) and the long flight path
of 0.72 m the mass resolution of the time-of-flight
system was good enough to separate masses 14 and 15.
Thus for these reactions one is able to measure
simultaneously angular distributions in both forward
and backward hemispheres by detection of a
particular heavy ion or its heavier complementary
product at forward lab angles. In addition partial
angular distributions leading to products in which
one of the heavy-ion products is in a
particle-unstable excited state have been measured.
